I'm not sure how to review this at all. I have never used mercurial in my whole life.
Does this change the visual behaviour of the mercurial prompt?
@mcornella, any ideas?

@roeniss I don't think we should use `may`. AFAIK, `may` gives the idea of possibility, and the user don't have that here. If they want the completion, they must use the legacy completion, since there is no other alternative because `docker completion` generates completion for `podman`, not `docker`. Maybe just `You need`, without `may`. Please take this tip with a spoon of salt since English is not my mother language.
I also think we rephrase `podman-docker wrapper` to `Podman's Docker wrapper` because even the package on Debian/Ubuntu is called `podman-docker`, may could be different for Arch or Red Hat-like, something like `docker-podman-compat` (I'm guessing here).
Also, you have an empty file called `a` that I think it was added accidentally.

@carlosala Hi! Following up on this PR after 3 months of inactivity. This addresses a long-standing UX issue (#4390) with a minimal, non-breaking change that adds confirmation before overwriting `.zshrc` files.
Since @mcornella has already approved and the implementation is straightforward, could we move this forward? Happy to address any concerns if needed.
Thanks!

Hi @Kludex! As far as I remember ggl and the rest were made to support many different workflows, including ggpull, etc. This was added a while back (years ago), and we only documented the deprecation but not made the code change.

I can understand how that can be hard to get used to, especially when the aliases have been long working. I'm OK with reverting the deprecation of those 3 aliases.

@rivenirvana could you PR a revert of that change, i.e. undeprecate the aliases? `current_branch` is OK to be deprecated, it's usually a set it and forget it kind of thing.

Since I wanted to try this plugin ASAP, I forked your fork, stripped down everything and kept only the plugin which can be installed as standalone inside ohmyzsh/plugins folder.
Of course this is only a temp solution in the meantime while the pull requests get eventually merged.
